    "last_activity_date" : 1262599323,
    "creation_date" : 1262599323,
    "answer_id" : 1998559,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Java generics uses type erasure. The bit in the angle brackets (<code>&lt;Integer&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;String&gt;</code>) gets removed, so you'd end up with two methods that have an identical signature (the <code>add(Set)</code> you see in the error). That's not allowed because the runtime wouldn't know which to use for each case.</p>\n\n<p>If Java ever gets reified generics, then you could do this, but that's probably unlikely now.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 19462,
        "reputation" : 104083,
        "user_id" : 45664,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 91,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/YPWiu.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Andrzej Doyle",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/45664/andrzej-doyle"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 6,
      "creation_date" : 1262612456,
      "post_id" : 1998561,
      "comment_id" : 1918222,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
      "body" : "It&#39;s technically just the raw type <code>Set</code>.  Generics don&#39;t exist in byte code, they&#39;re syntactic sugar for casting and provide compile-time type safety."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 69248,
      "reputation" : 2180,
      "user_id" : 201619,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9700507b9f8f885008fbaf5bca1bbe1b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "rossoft",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/201619/rossoft"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1262599367,
    "creation_date" : 1262599367,
    "answer_id" : 1998561,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>It could be possible that the compiler translates Set(Integer) to Set(Object) in java byte code. If this is the case, Set(Integer) would be used only at compile phase for syntax checking.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14954,
      "reputation" : 48295,
      "user_id" : 31136,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 50,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c4d219e169610bd0ab7a4bcf5762e3a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "bruno conde",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/31136/bruno-conde"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 52,
    "last_activity_date" : 1323644733,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495540973,
    "creation_date" : 1262599460,
    "answer_id" : 1998568,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is because Java Generics are implemented with <a href=\"http://www.angelikalanger.com/GenericsFAQ/FAQSections/TechnicalDetails.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Type Erasure</a>.</p>\n\n<p><s>Your methods would be translated, at compile time, to something like:</s></p>\n\n<p>Method resolution occurs at compile time and doesn't consider type parameters. (<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/8467804/31136\">see erickson's answer</a>)</p>\n\n<pre><code>void add(Set ii);\nvoid add(Set ss);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Both methods have the same signature without the type parameters, hence the error.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2496,
        "reputation" : 270515,
        "user_id" : 3474,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 83,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ffbf4e85b8ffbae4e9039b9c0cf07bc8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "erickson",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3474/erickson"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 7,
      "creation_date" : 1323638462,
      "post_id" : 1998571,
      "comment_id" : 10471966,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "It&#39;s true that the JVM <i>runtime</i> has no information to distinguish each <code>Set</code>, but since the method resolution happens at compile-time, when the necessary information is available, this isn&#39;t relevant. The problem is that allowing these overloads would conflict with the allowance for raw types, so they were made illegal in the Java syntax."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 283609,
        "reputation" : 46760,
        "user_id" : 581205,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 72,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9a46cf0cb855b5b591740cfd7b9f81a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "maaartinus",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/581205/maaartinus"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 2496,
        "reputation" : 270515,
        "user_id" : 3474,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 83,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ffbf4e85b8ffbae4e9039b9c0cf07bc8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "erickson",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3474/erickson"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1537284419,
      "post_id" : 1998571,
      "comment_id" : 91724862,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@erickson Even when the compiler knows what method to call, it can&#39;t as in the bytecode, they both look exactly the same. You&#39;d need to change how a method call gets specified, as <code>(Ljava&#47;util&#47;Collection;)Ljava&#47;util&#47;List;</code> doesn&#39;t work. You could use  <code>(Ljava&#47;util&#47;Collection&lt;String&gt;;)Ljava&#47;util&#47;List&lt;String&gt;;</code>, but that&#39;s an incompatible change and you&#39;d run into unsolvable problems in places where all you have is an erased type. You&#39;d probably have to drop erasure completely, but that&#39;s pretty complicated."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2496,
        "reputation" : 270515,
        "user_id" : 3474,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 83,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ffbf4e85b8ffbae4e9039b9c0cf07bc8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "erickson",
