      "creation_date" : 1537289041,
      "post_id" : 1998571,
      "comment_id" : 91727437,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@maaartinus Yes, I agree that you&#39;d have to change the method specifier. I&#39;m trying to get at some of the unsolvable problems that led them to give up on that attempt."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12262,
      "reputation" : 104314,
      "user_id" : 24054,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/24059909b82438e84ac480148dbdc4d6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "kgiannakakis",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/24054/kgiannakakis"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 29,
    "last_activity_date" : 1262599509,
    "creation_date" : 1262599509,
    "answer_id" : 1998571,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>The problem is that <code>Set&lt;Integer&gt;</code> and <code>Set&lt;String&gt;</code> are actually treated as a <code>Set</code> from the JVM. Selecting a type for the Set (String or Integer in your case) is only syntactic sugar used by the compiler. The JVM can't distinguish between <code>Set&lt;String&gt;</code> and <code>Set&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
