    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Define a single Method without type like <code>void add(Set ii){}</code></p>\n\n<p>You can mention the type while calling the method based on your choice. It will work for any type of set.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10687763,
      "reputation" : 365,
      "user_id" : 7867773,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/188160511693787/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Kote Isaev",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7867773/kote-isaev"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1575120991,
    "creation_date" : 1575120991,
    "answer_id" : 59116683,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I bumped into this when tried to write something like:\n<code>Continuable&lt;T&gt; callAsync(Callable&lt;T&gt; code) {....}</code>\nand\n<code>Continuable&lt;Continuable&lt;T&gt;&gt; callAsync(Callable&lt;Continuable&lt;T&gt;&gt; veryAsyncCode) {...}</code>\nThey become for compiler the 2 definitions of\n<code>Continuable&lt;&gt; callAsync(Callable&lt;&gt; veryAsyncCode) {...}</code></p>\n\n<p>The type erasure literally means erasing of type arguments information from generics.\nThis is VERY annoying, but this is a limitation that will be with Java for while.\nFor constructors case not much can be done, 2 new subclasses specialized with different parameters in constructor for example.\nOr use initialization methods instead... (virtual constructors?) with different names...</p>\n\n<p>for similar operation methods renaming would help, like </p>\n\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>class Test{\n   void addIntegers(Set&lt;Integer&gt; ii){}\n   void addStrings(Set&lt;String&gt; ss){}\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Or with some more descriptive names, self-documenting for oyu cases, like <code>addNames</code> and <code>addIndexes</code> or such.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4670913,
      "reputation" : 3900,
      "user_id" : 3782729,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a2d9f3064e58892b2515017470e87ef?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Piotr Rogowski",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3782729/piotr-rogowski"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1674820442,
    "creation_date" : 1674820442,
    "answer_id" : 75257755,
    "question_id" : 1998544,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In this case can use this structure:</p>\n<pre><code>class Test{\n   void add(Integer ... ii){}\n   void add(String ... ss){}\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>and inside methods can create target collections</p>\n<pre><code>void add(Integer ... values){\n   this.values = Arrays.asList(values);\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
